<HEADLINE>
<P>
ART; 
</P>
<P>
THE READERS TALK BACK -- IN PERSON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CATHY CURTIS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It's always an eye-opener for me to get out from behind my computer terminal 
and meet some of the people who read this column. It's a great way to find out 
what people are thinking and what they really care about. The other day, I gave 
a talk sponsored by the Works Gallery at Five Feet Two restaurant in Newport 
Beach, and when it was over the audience had many questions. 
</P>
<P>
I had said in the talk that the kind of contemporary art most interesting to me 
these days is "conceptual" in a broad sense -- meaning that the ideas 
motivating the work are ultimately more important than its level of craft, 
finish or emotional expression. Happily, the new wave of conceptual work tends 
to be more engagingly quizzical on a visual level than the old wave, which 
consisted largely of printed texts, with no visual content at all. 
</P>
<P>
I made a stumbling attempt to describe some of the motivations of conceptual 
artists, such as their investigations into the clash of cultures, tastes and 
attitudes that exist side by side in daily life. This is an aspect of the 
culturally relativistic outlook that conservatives love to hate. 
</P>
<P>
Free to forage high and low for material, fascinated by the phenomenon of style 
and beholden to no central definition of beauty or truth, conceptual artists 
are researchers into the way we process information, the way we make 
connections between one thing and another. 
</P>
<P>
One woman in the audience said she figured that she could have the same 
thoughts without bothering to look at the art. She wanted to know what I 
thought about the contemporary watercolor painting scene. 
</P>
<P>
To my mind, watercolor painting -- once a sideline of such significant American 
artists as John Marin, Charles Demuth and Winslow Homer -- has become the 
province of genteel illustrators utterly uninvolved with the issues of 
contemporary art. The notion of even bothering to differentiate one 
watercolorist from another frankly seems a waste of time. 
</P>
<P>
I think I said something a tad less dismissive to the woman. Sometimes it seems 
incredible how few things two people who both profess a love of art can have in 
common. For the most part, it's the old split between those who like to think 
of art as a friendly, constant North Star and those who view art as a shooting 
star, a brief burst of illumination that dashes off to points unknown. 
</P>
<P>
An older man in the audience also seemed plainly uncomfortable with all this 
talk about conceptual art. He offered the example of British painter Francis 
Bacon, subject of a recent retrospective at the Los Angeles County Museum of 
Art, as the kind of artist who really grabs the viewer with the force of his 
expressive painting. 
</P>
<P>
I agreed that Bacon's work is powerful stuff, but I said I wouldn't rush to 
embrace a 23-year-old fresh out of art school who painted in the same way. Why? 
Well, Bacon, who was born in 1909 and began painting in the 1930s, is part of 
the generation that gave birth to Existentialism. But that philosophy is no 
longer current, any more than wearing sandals and black stockings or having 
coffeehouse discussions about banning the bomb. 
</P>
<P>
Today's exciting young artists respond to the social and intellectual currents 
in the air today. It's the same in any field. Why don't they make movies like 
they used to, people always want to know. Why did popular music ever forsake 
the Big Band era? What happened to rock after the '60s? But, like it or not, 
life is different today, and our art forms respond to that difference. 
</P>
<P>
Another woman said she felt that my talk -- which included squawks about the 
dullness and low level of the local gallery scene -- was too negative. She 
wanted to hear what people in Orange County could do to help make the art scene 
more sophisticated and well-informed. It was a good question, and I 
unfortunately gave it short shrift. 
</P>
<P>
"Support your local museums!" I said off the top of my head. I suggested 
visiting top Los Angeles galleries as well as museums to get an idea of the 
range of good contemporary art. I could have added becoming more involved with 
community art centers and trying to "infiltrate" the ranks of stodgy boards of 
trustees. 
</P>
<P>
When you're confused or just need information, ask questions of curators 
(museum support groups provide access) and art dealers. Develop opinions. Worry 
less about what your friends think. What do you think? 
</P>
<P>
My most uncomfortable moment came when someone asked me what I collect. It was 
a perfectly reasonable question. It's just that I don't collect art. "I collect 
books," I murmured. It's true. I own hundreds of volumes: fiction, biography, 
books on art and dance. But I go home and feel perfectly content to see nothing 
but light and shadow making their mark on the white walls of my tiny vintage 
house. 
</P>
<P>
I said I could imagine inviting artists to do site-specific installations on a 
rotating basis, had I any space to spare. I said some critics deliberately 
don't collect in any field of art about which they write, for 
conflict-of-interest reasons. 
</P>
<P>
Ah, excuses, excuses. Well, I love music but I also like to spend hours at home 
with the stereo off, just vaguely aware of the sounds of domestic life: the 
rustle of trees, the muffled sounds of kids playing ball, the hum of the 
refrigerator. Maybe not owning any art to speak of is a form of visual R&amp;R. 
You tell me. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Drawing, Hands, STEVE LOPEZ / Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
