</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
ASBURY PARK, N.J. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A closed museum boasting the world's largest collection of Bruce Springsteen 
memorabilia wants to sell it intact for at least $50,000. 
</P>
<P>
Among the items for sale: a surfboard, Springsteen's 1970 driver's license, his 
draft card and a rare 1966 unreleased single by Springsteen's first band, the 
Castiles. 
</P>
<P>
The Asbury Park Rock 'n' Roll Museum shut down last year. 
</P>
<P>
Billy Smith, a co-owner of most of the Springsteen artifacts, said he hopes a 
buyer will keep them in Asbury Park, where the singer got his start. 
</P>
<P>
"Hopefully, somebody will buy this stuff and display it," Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
Asbury Park, a down-at-the-heels resort town, is the setting for some of 
Springsteen's early songs. 
</P>
<P>
The museum was in the Palace Amusement Arcade, where parts of Springsteen's 
"Tunnel of Love" video were shot. When the arcade closed last year, so did the 
museum, and its contents went into storage. 
</P>
